## Honest Limitations

This adapter is a minimal-posture adapter. It does **not** match Claude Code's
coverage. Read this section before relying on it.

- **No automatic telemetry.** {{TELEMETRY_GAP}}. Without telemetry, the weekly
  dead-skills report has no data to work with — it will report "no telemetry"
  until you instrument something (Aider has no `PreToolUse`-style hook).
- **No skill loader.** Aider has no `skills/` directory contract. The router
  table above is reasoned over inline; the `skills/` dir and its README ship the
  SKILL.md frontmatter convention so the router can point at curated skills, but
  Aider will not auto-load them.
- **No lifecycle hooks.** No SessionEnd hook means memory entries are written by
  hand. The memory protocol above documents where to write them.
- **No native memory store.** Aider does not persist a memory index of its own.
  `MEMORY.md` + `memory/<bucket>/` are plain files you maintain manually.
- **No scheduled prune.** The weekly auto-prune is a script you run manually or
  schedule via Windows Task Scheduler / cron / launchd / systemd timer. Grace
  period is **{{GRACE_PERIOD_DAYS}} days** of zero invocations before a skill
  becomes a prune candidate.
- **Posture is loaded, not enforced.** `read: CONVENTIONS.md` makes Aider treat
  this file as read-only context on every run; it does not give Aider hooks or a
  router engine. The substance is here for the model to reason over.

If you want Claude-Code-grade automation, use the `claude-code` adapter. The
aider adapter trades automation for a clean, portable on-ramp into Aider.
